def chi_sq_test(cross_tabs, m):
    """
    Prints the Chi-Squared Statistic, p-value, degress of freedom from a Chi-Squared test,
    and Cramer coefficient

    Args:
        cross_tabs: A crosstab dataframe.
    """
    chi2, p, dof, con_table = ss.chi2_contingency(cross_tabs)
    print(f"chi-squared = {chi2}")
    print(f"p value = {p}")
    print(f"degrees of freedom = {dof}")
    print(f"{m} coefficient = {ss.contingency.association(cross_tabs, method=m)}\n\n")

def run_mann_whitney_with_plot(df, target, vars_list):
    p_values = []

    for var in vars_list:
        group_0 = df[df[target] == 0][var].dropna()
        group_1 = df[df[target] == 1][var].dropna()

        stat, p = mannwhitneyu(group_0, group_1, alternative='two-sided')
        p_values.append(p)

        print(f"-> Mann-Whitney U test for {var} with target '{target}'")
        print(f"U statistic = {stat:.2e}")
        print(f"p-value = {p:.2e}")

        if p < 0.05:
            print(f" Diferena estatisticamente significativa entre os grupos de '{target}' para '{var}'\n")
        else:
            print(f" Sem diferena estatisticamente significativa entre os grupos de '{target}' para '{var}'\n")


def bar_plot(
    figsize, title, data, x, y, xlabel=None, ylabel=None,
    palette=None, subtitle=None, hue=None, hue_title=None,
    legend_loc='best', padding=0, ax=None, order=None
):
    """
    Plots a bar plot using seaborn.

    Parmetros:
        figsize (tuple): figure size (width, height)
        title (str): main title for plot
        data (DataFrame): dataframe with data to plot
        x (str): x axis column
        y (str): y axis column
        xlabel (str, optional): x axis label (default: None)
        ylabel (str, optional): y axis label (default: None)
        palette (str ou lista, optional): color palette for plot elements (default: None)
        subtitle (str, optional): subtitle for plot (default: None)
        hue (str, optional): column to be grouped (default: None)
        hue_title (str, optional): title for group legend (default: None)
        legend_loc (str ou tupla, optional): group legend location (default: 'best')
        padding (float, optional): spacing between label and bar label (default: 0)
        ax (Axes, optional): subplot instance to plot (default: None)
        order (list, optional): Order of bars (default: None)
    """

    if ax is None:
        # Cria a figura para o grfico
        fig = plt.figure(figsize=figsize)
        ax = fig.add_subplot()
    else:
        # Usa a subplot fornecida
        fig = ax.get_figure()

    # Ttulo e subttulo alinhados  direita com ajuste de espaamento
    fig.suptitle(title, fontsize=14, y=1.03)

    ax.set_title(subtitle, fontsize=10, fontstyle='italic')

    # Grfico de barras
    ax = sns.barplot(data=data, x=x, y=y, errorbar=None, palette=palette, hue=hue, ax=ax, order=order)

    # Rtulos do eixo
    ax.set_xlabel(xlabel)
    ax.set_ylabel(ylabel)

    # Adiciona rtulos nas barras
    for c in ax.containers:
        ax.bar_label(
            c, fmt=lambda x: f"{x:0.0f}%" if x > 0 else "",
            padding=padding, color="White", fontweight="bold"
        )

    # Adiciona ttulos na legenda (hue)
    if hue:
        handles, labels = ax.get_legend_handles_labels()
        ax.legend(handles, labels, title=hue_title, loc=legend_loc)

-> Feature Preset_1 with target 'Fail'
chi-squared = 1.5412525683687348
p value = 0.46272318133467893
degrees of freedom = 2
cramer coefficient = 0.04907348711958574


-> Feature Preset_2 with target 'Fail'
chi-squared = 9.933263079440607
p value = 0.1923870435673064
degrees of freedom = 7
cramer coefficient = 0.1245821960057935

Statistical Interpretation:

1. High p-value (> 0.05): Both tests fail to reject the null hypothesis.

This means there is insufficient statistical evidence to confirm an association between Preset_1 or Preset_2 and Failure. In simple terms: failure patterns occur similarly regardless of the Preset value.

2. Cramr's V: Strength of Association Typical Values:

  • 0.00 - 0.10: Almost no association.

  • 0.10 - 0.20: Weak association.

  • 0.20 - 0.40: Moderate.

  • '>=0.40: Strong.

Results:

Preset_1: 0.049 Virtually no association.

Preset_2: 0.125 Weak association, but not yet statistically significant.

==================CONCLUSION=====================

The tests indicate that none of the variables Preset_1 and Preset_2 present a statistically significant association with the occurrence of failure. The strength of association measured by Cramr's coefficient is weak for Preset_2 (0.12) and practically zero for Preset_1 (0.05), suggesting that these variables alone do not explain equipment failure well.

4.0 Data Preparation

In[33]:
df4 = df_train.copy().reset_index(drop=True)

Data Preparation Feature Engineering Justification

Below are the transformations applied to enhance the dataset and improve model performance, along with their justifications:

In[34]:
# RMS of Vibration X, Y and Z (root mean square)
df4['Vibration_RMS'] = np.sqrt(df4['VibrationX']**2 + df4['VibrationY']**2 + df4['VibrationZ']**2)

# Data Transformation
old_cols_temp_press = ['Temperature', 'Pressure']
df4['Temp_Pressure'] = df4[old_cols_temp_press[0]] * df4[old_cols_temp_press[1]]
df4['Preset_1'] = df4['Preset_1'].astype(int)
df4['Preset_2'] = df4['Preset_2'].astype(int)

Vibration_RMS (Root Mean Square of Vibrations)

Rationale:
In systems where vibration is measured in three axes (X, Y, Z), the overall vibration intensity is best represented by the Root Mean Square (RMS). This transformation combines the directional components into a single metric that reflects the total vibrational energy of the system.

Why it matters:
This metric is widely used in industrial monitoring for machinery health and fault detection, as it provides a comprehensive measure of vibration severity, independent of direction.

Temp_Pressure (Interaction between Temperature and Pressure)

Rationale:
Multiplying temperature and pressure creates an interaction feature that captures nonlinear relationships between the two variables. This is important because in physical and mechanical systems, the joint effect of temperature and pressure can significantly influence performance and failure risk.

Why it matters:
This interaction term allows predictive models to learn more complex patterns that would not be captured by the variables independently.

Conversion of Preset_1 and Preset_2 to int

Rationale:
These variables represent discrete operational configurations. Converting them to integers ensures they are treated as categorical numeric codes rather than continuous variables.

Why it matters:
This step improves consistency and facilitates correct grouping, aggregation, and modeling behavior, particularly in classification tasks or when encoding is needed later.

Boruta is a wrapper method built around a Random Forest classifier that performs all-relevant feature selection. It iteratively compares the importance of each actual feature against randomized (shadow) features, helping identify variables with real predictive power.

Outcome:

Final Decision Top 3 Features

To simplify the model and reduce dimensionality while preserving performance, we selected only the top 3 features that were consistently ranked highly by both methods:

  • Vibration_RMS Overall vibration magnitude
  • Frequency Operation frequency
  • Temp_Pressure Interaction between temperature and pressure

Why this choice?

  • These variables had high importance in both Boruta and feature importance.
  • They are interpretable and physically relevant in the context of industrial fault detection.
  • A smaller feature set reduces overfitting risk and model complexity, which is especially valuable in smaller datasets or noisy environments.

6.0.1 Oversampling

Addressing Class Imbalance with SMOTE:

Before training the machine learning models, it is crucial to handle the class imbalance present in the target variable. Imbalanced data can lead to biased models that favor the majority class and fail to generalize well to minority class instances.

To mitigate this, I applied the SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Over-sampling Technique) method. SMOTE works by generating synthetic examples for the minority class based on feature-space similarities between existing minority instances. This improves the model's ability to learn decision boundaries for both classes.

In[42]:

6.3 XGBoost

To further improve performance, I applied XGBoost, a powerful gradient boosting algorithm known for its high efficiency and predictive accuracy. XGBoost builds decision trees sequentially, where each new tree aims to correct errors made by the previous ones.

XGBoost also includes regularization to prevent overfitting and has built-in handling of missing values, making it suitable for structured/tabular data like this dataset. Given its popularity in data science competitions and real-world applications, XGBoost is a strong candidate for final model selection.

In[49]:

6.4 Logistic Regression

Lastly, I evaluated Logistic Regression, a simple yet effective linear model for binary classification. It serves as an interpretable baseline for comparison with tree-based models.

Although Logistic Regression may not capture complex patterns as well as ensemble methods, it provides valuable insights into the linear relationship between input features and the target variable. Its also computationally efficient and performs well when the assumptions of linearity are approximately met.

In[51]:
# Initialize the Logistic Regression Classifier
model = LogisticRegression(random_state=42, solver='liblinear') # 'liblinear' is good for small datasets and binary classification

# Train the model
# Logistic Regression doesn't have a max_depth parameter, so we'll iterate through regularization strengths (C) instead

I selected Logistic Regression as one of the final models primarily because of its interpretability, robustness, and ability to provide probability estimates. In the context of equipment failure detection, false negatives are particularly dangerous, as they mean we fail to predict an actual failure which could lead to operational disruption or safety issues.

With Logistic Regression, we can fine-tune the decision threshold to favor high recall, ensuring we catch nearly all potential failures. Even if this leads to more false positives (false alarms), it is a safer and more conservative approach for this kind of industrial application.
